<|startoftext|>So yes, @MSNBC is part of the cable swamp. Bravo to @jakebackpack for the careful profile. But focusing on their specific failures vis-a-vis American politics only scratches the surface. We also have to reconsider our place in the broader world of news too.<|endoftext|>
<|startoftext|>But its also an artifact of being in a corner of Academia that positions the US in these broader geopolitical developments. As with writing on borders (@reecejhawaii, @Geopolitics2020), migration (@UnlawfulEntries), populism (@CasMudde), etc.<|endoftext|>
<|startoftext|>Maybe this jadedness comes from the fact that I live in Europe - I teach @PolSciLeiden and interact primarily with international students. This makes MSNBC's brand of "left Americana" seem particularly empty.<|endoftext|>
<|startoftext|>Not to mention all the "Green New Deals" across Europe and worldwide. Do these not matter? (Of course they do). But MSNBC ignores them because it doesn't fit into their narrative about Trump and the Rep/Dem turf war.<|endoftext|>
<|startoftext|>Also, for all the attention to Trump's wall, its remarkable how infrequently the channel discusses all the other walls popping up around the world. Are these phenomena related? Were these other attempts at border security effective? What kind of domestic politics produced them?<|endoftext|>
<|startoftext|>For example: for all the focus on Trump, there is a tremendous lack of attention on MSNBC to other forms of populism/xenophobia in other parts of the world - Brexit, Brazil, Hungary. Are we not a part of this phenomenon? Can we learn nothing by discussing them in tandem?<|endoftext|>
<|startoftext|>So its good that this profile is out there - I think we need to start broadening our horizons about what counts as newsworthy in the US, and holding stations like MSBNC to account. (Voting with our feet if we have to).<|endoftext|>
<|startoftext|>But the main problem with MSNBC is it further provincializes the left. Americans, even educated ones, are rarely well informed about the rest of the world, and MSNBC's obsession with the petty intrigue of washington politics soaks all attention away from global subjects 3/<|endoftext|>
